1
00:00:31,365 --> 00:00:35,953
BEYOND THE BAR

2
00:00:39,540 --> 00:00:40,874
Do you remember?

3
00:00:40,958 --> 00:00:43,210
Of course she does.
She was eight. Why wouldn't she?

4
00:00:43,293 --> 00:00:45,212
Well, she was young, so she might not.

5
00:00:49,591 --> 00:00:51,385
Because I can't do it.

6
00:00:55,639 --> 00:00:56,932
Sir!

7
00:00:57,724 --> 00:00:59,810
Is there a doctor on board?

8
00:01:00,352 --> 00:01:02,104
- Is anyone a doctor?
- I'm a doctor.

9
00:01:03,397 --> 00:01:04,898
- Oh, you're--
- Can you help us?

10
00:01:05,440 --> 00:01:07,359
Together now. One, two, three.

11
00:01:08,360 --> 00:01:10,153
Let's get him on his back.

12
00:01:17,995 --> 00:01:20,414
<i>- He's a monster.</i>
<i>- Kim Byeong-su was arrested in Eunseong</i>

13
00:01:20,497 --> 00:01:22,624
<i>on charges of kidnapping</i>
<i>and sexually assaulting</i>

14
00:01:22,708 --> 00:01:24,126
<i>a seven-year-old girl.</i>

15
00:01:24,209 --> 00:01:28,380
<i>Confirmed reports indicate</i>
<i>the victim has suffered</i>

16
00:01:28,463 --> 00:01:31,341
<i>physical and psychological trauma</i>
<i>that could be life-threatening.</i>

17
00:01:31,425 --> 00:01:33,468
<i>Mr. Kim claims he was intoxicated,</i>

18
00:01:33,552 --> 00:01:36,054
<i>resulting in his diminished capacity</i>
<i>at the time of the crime.</i>

19
00:01:36,513 --> 00:01:38,307
APRIL 2015

20
00:01:38,390 --> 00:01:39,516
Please make way.

21
00:01:54,740 --> 00:01:56,491
What happened? What's her name?

22
00:01:56,575 --> 00:01:58,577
Kim Min-sol. Age seven.

23
00:01:58,660 --> 00:02:00,370
Min-sol.

24
00:02:00,454 --> 00:02:02,331
Can you hear me, Min-sol?

25
00:02:16,720 --> 00:02:20,390
Why did you wake up? Are you in pain?

26
00:02:21,224 --> 00:02:22,309
Are you feeling okay?

27
00:02:22,976 --> 00:02:23,977
It's all right.

28
00:02:24,519 --> 00:02:27,898
Don't worry, I'll be right here.
You can go to sleep.

29
00:02:29,232 --> 00:02:32,653
You're such a good girl. Sleep well now.

30
00:02:33,528 --> 00:02:35,697
MAY 2020

31
00:02:37,240 --> 00:02:38,325
Is it a stab wound?

32
00:02:49,836 --> 00:02:53,215
No. I refuse to treat him.

33
00:02:53,298 --> 00:02:55,967
It'll take 40 minutes
just to transport him to another hospital.

34
00:02:56,051 --> 00:02:58,095
That would increase the risk of death.

35
00:02:58,595 --> 00:03:00,138
- So?
- Pardon?

36
00:03:01,473 --> 00:03:02,683
What's going on?

37
00:03:05,644 --> 00:03:06,687
Well…

38
00:03:07,771 --> 00:03:09,690
As a doctor, how could you say that?

39
00:03:09,773 --> 00:03:11,733
Do you know how many hospitals
there are in Seoul?

40
00:03:11,817 --> 00:03:14,736
I mean, what are the odds
he'd end up in my care?

41
00:03:14,820 --> 00:03:17,280
Me, Min-sol's doctor, of all people?

42
00:03:17,364 --> 00:03:20,409
This is a sign from above not to save him.

43
00:03:20,492 --> 00:03:22,160
A doctor's job is to save people.

44
00:03:22,244 --> 00:03:24,454
You don't get to decide
who deserves to live.

45
00:03:24,538 --> 00:03:26,289
I'm not suggesting we kill him.

46
00:03:26,373 --> 00:03:28,500
If he's dying anyway,
why not just let him?

47
00:03:28,583 --> 00:03:29,668
How could you…

48
00:03:29,751 --> 00:03:32,087
How can you say such things
and call yourself a doctor?

49
00:03:32,170 --> 00:03:34,840
Did you not see the condition
Min-sol arrived in?

50
00:03:34,923 --> 00:03:38,677
I still remember
every excruciating detail of that day.

51
00:03:39,344 --> 00:03:42,180
The sheer brutality and cruelty
haunts me to this day.

52
00:03:42,681 --> 00:03:46,017
A helpless seven-year-old child
had to go through that.

53
00:03:46,685 --> 00:03:48,437
What if we save him,

54
00:03:48,520 --> 00:03:50,897
and that leads
to another victim like Min-sol?

55
00:03:50,981 --> 00:03:53,567
He'll be released in a few years,

56
00:03:53,650 --> 00:03:55,861
and he will live on for decades.

57
00:03:55,944 --> 00:03:57,362
I don't know about all that.

58
00:03:57,446 --> 00:03:59,656
Right now,
all I see is a critical patient.

59
00:04:00,365 --> 00:04:01,742
Move. I'll treat him.

60
00:04:08,165 --> 00:04:09,249
Doctor.

61
00:04:10,208 --> 00:04:11,710
Doctor!

62
00:04:11,793 --> 00:04:13,295
Yes? Oh, right.

63
00:04:23,096 --> 00:04:24,598
He is in cardiac tamponade.

64
00:04:24,681 --> 00:04:27,058
Fluid is building up around his heart
and compressing it.

65
00:04:27,142 --> 00:04:29,060
Emergency treatment is required.

66
00:04:29,144 --> 00:04:31,605
Is there a pericardiocentesis needle
in the emergency kit?

67
00:04:31,688 --> 00:04:32,689
Just a moment.

68
00:04:33,523 --> 00:04:34,900
Let's get his shirt off first.

69
00:04:40,030 --> 00:04:41,406
Hand me the gloves.

70
00:04:50,957 --> 00:04:52,125
Hand me the needle.

71
00:05:17,734 --> 00:05:18,777
Damn it.

72
00:05:27,077 --> 00:05:31,998
THE RIGHT TO LIFE

73
00:05:35,627 --> 00:05:39,714
So, you're just going to let her run free
after she let my son die?

74
00:05:39,798 --> 00:05:42,551
DETECTIVE UNIT 2

75
00:05:42,676 --> 00:05:43,552
I mean,

76
00:05:43,635 --> 00:05:47,639
a doctor killed a person.
If that's not murder, then what is it?

77
00:05:47,722 --> 00:05:49,683
The police just handle the investigations.

78
00:05:49,766 --> 00:05:51,268
The prosecutor in charge will decide

79
00:05:51,351 --> 00:05:53,770
whether to indict for murder
or a different offense.

80
00:05:53,854 --> 00:05:56,940
You can talk to the prosecutor
after they're assigned.

81
00:05:57,691 --> 00:06:00,694
That doctor intentionally killed
my husband.

82
00:06:00,777 --> 00:06:01,820
That's why we're asking you

83
00:06:01,903 --> 00:06:03,613
to share what we said with the prosecutor

84
00:06:03,697 --> 00:06:05,615
or whoever has the power
to put her in jail.

85
00:06:05,699 --> 00:06:07,450
That's exactly what I'm saying.

86
00:06:07,534 --> 00:06:10,620
The last time my son
was in the emergency room,

87
00:06:10,704 --> 00:06:13,331
I heard every word that wench said.

88
00:06:13,832 --> 00:06:16,543
She clearly said
she wanted to kill my son.

89
00:06:16,626 --> 00:06:20,672
She's been bitter
ever since she failed to kill him.

90
00:06:20,755 --> 00:06:23,216
That's why when she saw him
on the plane this time,

91
00:06:23,300 --> 00:06:25,218
she seized her chance
to kill him for good.

92
00:06:26,052 --> 00:06:27,804
I can't believe this.

93
00:06:28,555 --> 00:06:32,142
How could they have let
that murderer perform emergency care?

94
00:06:33,018 --> 00:06:35,103
My goodness.

95
00:06:35,186 --> 00:06:36,980
- How unlucky could one be?
- Mother…

96
00:06:37,063 --> 00:06:39,608
Oh, Byeong-su.

97
00:06:40,400 --> 00:06:43,069
My poor Byeong-su.

98
00:06:43,862 --> 00:06:44,863
What?

99
00:06:46,781 --> 00:06:47,741
Hey, gather around.

100
00:06:47,824 --> 00:06:49,409
Come on. Hurry up.

101
00:06:50,535 --> 00:06:51,494
No way…

102
00:06:51,578 --> 00:06:53,622
JUNE PROMOTION NOTICE:
ATTORNEYS AND SECRETARIES

103
00:06:53,705 --> 00:06:55,373
Do Seung-jae?

104
00:06:55,999 --> 00:06:58,668
The ultimate salary thief at Yullim
is becoming a partner?

105
00:06:59,377 --> 00:07:01,087
Surely that's taking it too far.

106
00:07:02,422 --> 00:07:06,301
Most associates on this list
are notorious salary thieves.

107
00:07:06,384 --> 00:07:08,345
I thought with Ms. Kwon at the helm,

108
00:07:08,428 --> 00:07:10,764
the promotion system
would become more fair.

109
00:07:10,847 --> 00:07:12,432
This is just not right.

110
00:07:12,515 --> 00:07:15,977
Just be a little patient.
All these people will be gone soon enough.

111
00:07:16,603 --> 00:07:20,398
Even if they survive,
their days as salary thieves are over.

112
00:07:22,651 --> 00:07:23,902
Have you given it some thought?

113
00:07:25,528 --> 00:07:27,739
Yes, I have.

114
00:07:31,326 --> 00:07:32,994
But I like where I am now.

115
00:07:33,078 --> 00:07:35,246
I think I suffered enough at Yullim.

116
00:07:36,331 --> 00:07:37,624
I don't want to repeat that.

117
00:07:37,707 --> 00:07:38,917
You must know

118
00:07:39,542 --> 00:07:42,087
that your talents are being wasted
as an in-house counsel

119
00:07:42,170 --> 00:07:43,713
at a mid-sized company.

120
00:07:43,797 --> 00:07:45,256
Does that really matter?

121
00:07:46,091 --> 00:07:47,133
Peace of mind is enough.

122
00:07:50,261 --> 00:07:52,472
I can't promise anything else,

123
00:07:53,723 --> 00:07:55,100
but I can promise you this.

124
00:07:56,101 --> 00:07:59,896
I'm going to make Yullim
a place of justice.

125
00:08:00,814 --> 00:08:02,607
My definition of justice is quite simple.

126
00:08:02,691 --> 00:08:05,151
A system that evaluates
everyone's abilities impartially

127
00:08:05,235 --> 00:08:08,321
and allows people to succeed fairly
through effort and talent.

128
00:08:09,239 --> 00:08:13,535
You will end up being
the greatest beneficiary of that system.

129
00:08:22,335 --> 00:08:23,878
- Min-jeong.
- I'm busy.

130
00:08:34,180 --> 00:08:35,140
Hey, Min-jeong.

131
00:08:35,890 --> 00:08:37,017
Oh, right. I have that thing.

132
00:08:40,478 --> 00:08:41,688
What's wrong with her?

133
00:08:51,531 --> 00:08:52,782
I'm busy.

134
00:08:54,075 --> 00:08:56,202
Let's go grab a bite.

135
00:08:56,286 --> 00:08:57,370
I have plans.

136
00:08:58,580 --> 00:09:00,123
What are you looking at?

137
00:09:01,207 --> 00:09:02,917
Please leave. Let's talk later.

138
00:09:04,794 --> 00:09:05,837
Leave.

139
00:09:08,631 --> 00:09:09,883
It's Heo Min-jeong from Yullim.

140
00:09:10,759 --> 00:09:13,344
On page 39
of the legal due diligence report,

141
00:09:13,845 --> 00:09:17,223
I think we should double-check
whether the enforcement

142
00:09:17,307 --> 00:09:20,894
of the senior lender's security interest
could trigger a change of control.

143
00:09:20,977 --> 00:09:22,604
The senior loan…

144
00:09:22,687 --> 00:09:24,814
Kim Byeong-su's wife and mother

145
00:09:25,440 --> 00:09:27,275
come to the hospital every day

146
00:09:27,358 --> 00:09:29,360
to scream at me about being a murderer.

147
00:09:30,195 --> 00:09:32,155
They even spat in my face.

148
00:09:35,742 --> 00:09:37,160
What are they after?

149
00:09:37,786 --> 00:09:38,828
Well,

150
00:09:38,912 --> 00:09:41,331
it's probably money.

151
00:09:42,332 --> 00:09:44,000
And they keep threatening to file

152
00:09:44,084 --> 00:09:45,710
criminal charges for murder.

153
00:09:46,961 --> 00:09:50,757
What will happen to her
if she's indicted for murder?

154
00:09:51,382 --> 00:09:53,760
You need to prove intent
for a murder charge.

155
00:09:54,385 --> 00:09:56,304
Are they claiming
you intentionally killed him?

156
00:09:56,387 --> 00:09:58,556
Yes, it seems so.

157
00:09:58,640 --> 00:10:00,475
Could there be a reason for that?

158
00:10:02,727 --> 00:10:03,853
A few years ago,

159
00:10:04,395 --> 00:10:08,650
Mr. Kim was brought to the ER
after being stabbed while in custody.

160
00:10:09,359 --> 00:10:12,445
And I refused to treat him.

161
00:10:13,905 --> 00:10:16,658
It seems they heard me
talk about him back then.

162
00:10:17,367 --> 00:10:19,202
That's only scratching the surface.

163
00:10:19,869 --> 00:10:22,539
There couldn't be a worse twist of fate.

164
00:10:22,622 --> 00:10:25,917
My wife was the doctor
who treated the child victim.

165
00:10:26,000 --> 00:10:27,460
Then, a few years later,

166
00:10:27,544 --> 00:10:30,296
he ended up needing emergency care

167
00:10:30,380 --> 00:10:33,383
and was transported
to her hospital of all places. Right?

168
00:10:35,468 --> 00:10:39,139
And you saw him again on the plane?

169
00:10:40,140 --> 00:10:41,099
Yes.

170
00:10:41,724 --> 00:10:42,934
A cruel twist of fate indeed.

171
00:10:44,144 --> 00:10:48,022
Do you remember what you said
when you refused to treat him?

172
00:10:48,940 --> 00:10:49,858
Back then,

173
00:10:50,400 --> 00:10:54,529
I was so worked up,
so I don't remember exactly.

174
00:10:55,947 --> 00:10:59,325
But I think I said, "He doesn't deserve
to live. Just let him die."

175
00:10:59,826 --> 00:11:02,996
"Saving him might lead
to more victimized children."

176
00:11:03,079 --> 00:11:05,415
I believe it was
something along those lines.

177
00:11:06,291 --> 00:11:09,294
But to be fair, I wasn't wrong.

178
00:11:10,128 --> 00:11:12,505
Even though he failed in the end,

179
00:11:12,589 --> 00:11:15,049
he still attempted another kidnapping
of an eight-year-old girl.

180
00:11:15,133 --> 00:11:16,176
Yes, that's right.

181
00:11:16,801 --> 00:11:18,887
It hasn't been released to the press yet,

182
00:11:18,970 --> 00:11:21,723
but the report was filed,
and the investigation was underway.

183
00:11:23,224 --> 00:11:26,853
Although the investigation
closed when he died.

184
00:11:26,936 --> 00:11:29,564
Then was he on the plane to…

185
00:11:29,647 --> 00:11:32,942
Yes, it seems he was trying
to flee overseas.

186
00:11:38,990 --> 00:11:40,575
I need to ask you one question.

187
00:11:41,284 --> 00:11:42,827
Yes?

188
00:11:42,911 --> 00:11:44,746
Did you intentionally kill him?

189
00:11:45,955 --> 00:11:47,790
Sir, that question is a bit…

190
00:11:51,085 --> 00:11:51,961
No.

191
00:11:55,840 --> 00:11:57,133
Okay.

192
00:11:58,760 --> 00:12:01,179
We just need to confirm that
as a formality.

193
00:12:01,262 --> 00:12:02,180
I see.

194
00:12:05,600 --> 00:12:08,895
My heart was racing
as I was sitting there listening.

195
00:12:09,604 --> 00:12:12,607
Come on. Of course not.
She wouldn't have killed him on purpose.

196
00:12:12,690 --> 00:12:15,902
If she really wanted to kill him,
she could've just refused to treat him.

197
00:12:15,985 --> 00:12:17,445
Why bother pretending to save him?

198
00:12:17,528 --> 00:12:19,072
You don't know that.

199
00:12:19,572 --> 00:12:22,408
The prosecution could argue
that Dr. Choi didn't know it was him

200
00:12:22,492 --> 00:12:24,035
and went to provide emergency care

201
00:12:24,118 --> 00:12:27,413
but then changed her mind
once she found out who he was.

202
00:12:27,497 --> 00:12:29,040
That's just wrong.

203
00:12:29,123 --> 00:12:30,250
Dr. Choi might have said

204
00:12:30,333 --> 00:12:32,835
she wanted to kill him
in the heat of the moment,

205
00:12:32,919 --> 00:12:34,796
but there is a huge difference

206
00:12:34,879 --> 00:12:37,548
between wanting someone dead
and actually killing them.

207
00:12:37,632 --> 00:12:39,008
That's true.

208
00:12:39,717 --> 00:12:42,178
Honestly, if I'd been in her shoes,

209
00:12:42,262 --> 00:12:45,014
I also might have refused
to treat that monster.

210
00:12:45,723 --> 00:12:47,725
He did not deserve to be saved.

211
00:12:47,809 --> 00:12:48,893
Really?

212
00:12:48,977 --> 00:12:51,354
And here I thought you were
a highly ethical physician,

213
00:12:51,437 --> 00:12:53,106
committed to the Hippocratic Oath.

214
00:12:54,107 --> 00:12:55,608
Yes, you are right about that.

215
00:12:56,401 --> 00:12:59,195
"The worth of a life
is not relative but absolute."

216
00:12:59,279 --> 00:13:01,614
"No life shall be ranked above another."

217
00:13:01,698 --> 00:13:04,826
"All life must be treated equally."

218
00:13:04,909 --> 00:13:05,785
However…

219
00:13:06,577 --> 00:13:07,537
However?

220
00:13:08,162 --> 00:13:09,163
I hope

221
00:13:11,165 --> 00:13:14,794
Dr. Choi is declared
innocent without question.

222
00:13:16,170 --> 00:13:17,922
- Me too.
- Me too.

223
00:13:22,343 --> 00:13:25,221
<i>So, for Father's birthday this year,</i>

224
00:13:25,305 --> 00:13:28,099
<i>I'll be bringing</i>
<i>some homemade braised short ribs.</i>

225
00:13:28,182 --> 00:13:30,268
<i>How much are you going to make this time?</i>

226
00:13:30,351 --> 00:13:32,645
<i>I get nervous whenever you say</i>
<i>you're going to cook.</i>

227
00:13:32,729 --> 00:13:35,356
<i>You go so overboard in the kitchen.</i>

228
00:13:35,982 --> 00:13:38,443
<i>Listen, we have</i>
<i>over 100 people in our family.</i>

229
00:13:38,526 --> 00:13:42,697
<i>You won't find</i>
<i>a big family like ours anywhere else.</i>

230
00:13:42,780 --> 00:13:44,532
<i>It's seriously embarrassing.</i>

231
00:13:44,615 --> 00:13:48,036
<i>You don't know how lucky you are.</i>
<i>This is a blessing.</i>

232
00:13:48,661 --> 00:13:49,829
<i>Why is the youngest so quiet?</i>

233
00:13:49,912 --> 00:13:51,372
I'm here. I'm listening.

234
00:13:51,456 --> 00:13:52,582
<i>Oh, that's right.</i>

235
00:13:53,374 --> 00:13:55,376
<i>Remember my friend, Kwak Hye-jeong?</i>

236
00:13:55,460 --> 00:13:58,171
<i>Yeah, I heard she was filing for divorce.</i>

237
00:13:58,796 --> 00:13:59,839
<i>She is.</i>

238
00:14:00,340 --> 00:14:01,716
<i>She's been going through hell</i>

239
00:14:01,799 --> 00:14:04,802
<i>fighting her husband's lawyer</i>
<i>over the division of assets.</i>

240
00:14:04,886 --> 00:14:08,473
<i>Apparently, he has a top divorce lawyer,</i>

241
00:14:08,556 --> 00:14:10,516
<i>and her lawyer is falling a bit short.</i>

242
00:14:10,600 --> 00:14:12,977
<i>So she asked me to find out</i>

243
00:14:13,686 --> 00:14:16,731
<i>if my youngest brother</i>
<i>and his very reputable law firm</i>

244
00:14:16,814 --> 00:14:18,566
<i>could possibly take on her case.</i>

245
00:14:18,649 --> 00:14:21,736
No, I'm too busy.
Tell her to find someone else.

246
00:14:21,819 --> 00:14:23,654
<i>Seriously?</i>

247
00:14:23,738 --> 00:14:25,698
<i>She's a close friend of mine.</i>

248
00:14:25,782 --> 00:14:27,700
I normally don't handle divorces anyway.

249
00:14:27,784 --> 00:14:30,620
My colleague, Ms. Heo, usually handles…

250
00:14:36,417 --> 00:14:38,336
On second thought, sure.

251
00:14:39,128 --> 00:14:40,421
- I'll take it on.
<i>- Really?</i>

252
00:14:40,505 --> 00:14:44,050
Of course, I should help her.
You said she was a close friend.

253
00:14:44,133 --> 00:14:46,511
Give her my card
and tell her to stop by my office.

254
00:14:46,594 --> 00:14:48,262
<i>This is a surprise.</i>

255
00:14:48,346 --> 00:14:50,348
No, actually, while you're at it,

256
00:14:50,431 --> 00:14:53,142
ask her if she can stop by tomorrow.

257
00:14:53,226 --> 00:14:54,727
<i>- Should I?</i>
- Totally.

258
00:14:54,811 --> 00:14:57,855
<i>- Fantastic.</i>
<i>- Our baby is all grown up now.</i>

259
00:14:57,939 --> 00:14:59,440
Damn it. Stop calling me a baby.

260
00:14:59,524 --> 00:15:01,109
<i>Our cute little baby.</i>

261
00:15:01,192 --> 00:15:03,111
"Cute little baby"
is definitely off limits.

262
00:15:06,114 --> 00:15:07,448
PARTNER APPOINTMENT CEREMONY

263
00:15:08,866 --> 00:15:11,077
- Welcome.
- I look forward to working with you.

264
00:15:16,332 --> 00:15:19,627
- Let's do great things together.
- You'll have my full dedication.

265
00:15:24,090 --> 00:15:26,884
- I'm expecting great things.
- Yes, I'll do my best.

266
00:15:32,974 --> 00:15:34,892
- Congratulations.
- I'll give it my all.

267
00:15:37,937 --> 00:15:41,691
"We hereby appoint the above individual
as a partner of Yullim Law Firm."

268
00:15:41,774 --> 00:15:43,067
"Do Seung-jae, Esquire."

269
00:15:46,863 --> 00:15:48,698
What's with all the sulking?

270
00:15:48,781 --> 00:15:52,493
Aren't you happy to have made partner
two or three years earlier than most?

271
00:15:56,330 --> 00:16:00,084
Did you even read
the partner agreement before signing it?

272
00:16:00,168 --> 00:16:02,170
You know I hate reading contracts.

273
00:16:02,253 --> 00:16:03,504
I figured as much.

274
00:16:06,549 --> 00:16:09,969
We're officially hanging by a thread now.

275
00:16:10,052 --> 00:16:11,512
We don't even get a base salary.

276
00:16:11,596 --> 00:16:13,556
What are you talking about?

277
00:16:15,433 --> 00:16:17,393
After Ms. Kwon became
the managing partner,

278
00:16:17,477 --> 00:16:19,353
she did a complete overhaul
of the pay structure.

279
00:16:19,437 --> 00:16:21,022
Now, all partners are compensated

280
00:16:21,105 --> 00:16:23,691
through provisional payment
based on case intake or performance.

281
00:16:23,774 --> 00:16:25,193
There is no fixed salary anymore.

282
00:16:25,276 --> 00:16:26,152
Also,

283
00:16:27,111 --> 00:16:29,739
contract renewal will be determined
annually based on performance.

284
00:16:29,822 --> 00:16:30,907
What?

285
00:16:31,782 --> 00:16:34,535
If you keep performing like you do now,

286
00:16:34,619 --> 00:16:37,455
your paycheck next month will be zero won.

287
00:16:38,456 --> 00:16:39,916
And forget about getting renewed.

288
00:16:39,999 --> 00:16:41,209
What did you just say?

289
00:16:44,045 --> 00:16:46,005
This is just taking it way too far, sir.

290
00:16:46,088 --> 00:16:48,007
What exactly did we mess up so badly?

291
00:16:49,008 --> 00:16:52,762
Sir, are you really
just going to stand by and watch?

292
00:16:53,554 --> 00:16:56,641
We are Yullim, and Yullim is us.

293
00:16:56,724 --> 00:16:59,977
Organizational restructuring?
Sure, it sounds good in theory,

294
00:17:00,061 --> 00:17:03,397
but at the end of the day,
she is just tearing Yullim apart.

295
00:17:04,065 --> 00:17:05,608
Listen,

296
00:17:05,691 --> 00:17:08,694
I stepped down
as managing partner some time ago.

297
00:17:09,320 --> 00:17:11,864
Kwon Na-yeon is now
the managing partner at Yullim.

298
00:17:11,948 --> 00:17:15,076
Sir, are you really
going to abandon us like this?

299
00:17:15,159 --> 00:17:18,663
Abandon you?
How could you say such a thing?

300
00:17:18,746 --> 00:17:21,123
I am frustrated
with the situation as well.

301
00:17:21,207 --> 00:17:24,001
But I already handed over
my managerial authority to her.

302
00:17:24,085 --> 00:17:27,380
I would be overstepping
if I start telling her what to do.

303
00:17:27,463 --> 00:17:29,924
It would be bad optics.

304
00:17:30,007 --> 00:17:32,760
I mean, even Kwon Na-yeon

305
00:17:32,843 --> 00:17:34,887
would listen to what you have to say.

306
00:17:34,971 --> 00:17:36,722
Perhaps a little off-the-record chat--

307
00:17:36,806 --> 00:17:40,101
Come on now. There you go again with that.

308
00:17:40,184 --> 00:17:42,103
You just sound politically tone-deaf.

309
00:17:43,104 --> 00:17:45,147
Just take a second and think about it.

310
00:17:45,231 --> 00:17:47,608
Do you think Kwon Na-yeon
would even listen to me?

311
00:17:51,404 --> 00:17:53,364
Fine, I'll try to talk to her.

312
00:17:53,447 --> 00:17:55,366
But I can't guarantee anything.

313
00:17:55,449 --> 00:17:57,952
Thank you, sir. We appreciate it.

314
00:17:58,035 --> 00:18:00,746
We're counting on you, sir.

315
00:18:02,039 --> 00:18:04,292
- All right.
- We believe in you.

316
00:18:04,375 --> 00:18:05,918
Sure. Take care now.

317
00:18:11,007 --> 00:18:13,843
You don't know what you did wrong?

318
00:18:16,095 --> 00:18:20,224
There is no greater offense
than incompetence.

319
00:18:22,602 --> 00:18:23,519
Hey.

320
00:18:24,186 --> 00:18:26,105
Are you almost done
with the restructuring?

321
00:18:27,815 --> 00:18:29,400
All right.

322
00:18:30,234 --> 00:18:31,569
Let's start preparing now.

323
00:18:32,528 --> 00:18:33,529
Bye.

324
00:18:55,384 --> 00:18:58,804
Kim Byeong-su's family is pushing hard
for a murder indictment,

325
00:18:58,888 --> 00:19:01,349
and given her past refusal to treat him
and previous remarks,

326
00:19:01,432 --> 00:19:02,975
that indictment is highly probable.

327
00:19:03,059 --> 00:19:05,269
I believe we should submit
an opinion brief

328
00:19:05,353 --> 00:19:07,605
before the indictment is finalized
to stop it.

329
00:19:08,314 --> 00:19:09,690
What about negligent manslaughter?

330
00:19:09,774 --> 00:19:12,818
Given his death,
that charge seems unavoidable.

331
00:19:12,902 --> 00:19:14,987
We must prove

332
00:19:15,071 --> 00:19:18,449
that there was no direct causal link
between the act and the death.

333
00:19:19,992 --> 00:19:21,535
Have we secured an expert witness?

334
00:19:21,619 --> 00:19:24,372
Yes, we are meeting
with some doctors today.

335
00:19:24,997 --> 00:19:26,666
I'm sure some doctors will oppose.

336
00:19:26,749 --> 00:19:28,376
They'll cite medical ethics

337
00:19:28,459 --> 00:19:31,087
and take issue
with Ms. Choi's prior refusal to treat him

338
00:19:31,170 --> 00:19:33,005
or her past remarks about him.

339
00:19:33,756 --> 00:19:36,300
We must secure
as many expert opinions as we can

340
00:19:36,384 --> 00:19:39,387
to prepare for the possibility of opinions
favoring the prosecution.

341
00:19:39,470 --> 00:19:40,846
Understood.

342
00:19:44,141 --> 00:19:48,187
I have twin sisters
who are seven years old.

343
00:19:48,270 --> 00:19:51,399
We live ten minutes away
from where Kim Byeong-su used to live.

344
00:19:51,941 --> 00:19:53,943
I'd like to be assigned
to this case as well.

345
00:19:54,694 --> 00:19:55,611
- Me--
- Me too!

346
00:19:57,154 --> 00:19:58,739
These kids.

347
00:20:03,577 --> 00:20:04,870
Fine, I'll allow it.

348
00:20:07,665 --> 00:20:08,833
The truth

349
00:20:09,792 --> 00:20:12,878
can look very different,
depending on how light is cast on it.

350
00:20:14,171 --> 00:20:16,632
Attorneys do not distort the truth.

351
00:20:17,299 --> 00:20:21,846
We help ensure
it doesn't get skewed in the wrong light

352
00:20:21,929 --> 00:20:26,267
due to a client's legal inexperience
or the inflexibility of the law.

353
00:20:33,983 --> 00:20:35,317
- Thank you.
- Thank you.

354
00:20:41,866 --> 00:20:42,950
Mr. Yoon.

355
00:20:43,033 --> 00:20:46,454
I'm considering taking on a divorce case
that involves an acquaintance of mine.

356
00:20:46,537 --> 00:20:48,247
Divorce is Ms. Heo Min-jeong's specialty--

357
00:20:48,330 --> 00:20:50,040
I was hoping to co-chair with her.

358
00:20:50,583 --> 00:20:52,251
Well, if you involve Ms. Heo,

359
00:20:52,334 --> 00:20:53,961
Mr. Kim may contest acquisition credit--

360
00:20:54,044 --> 00:20:56,088
She can take the acquisition
and performance credit.

361
00:20:56,172 --> 00:20:57,506
I'll just do the work.

362
00:20:59,675 --> 00:21:00,551
Aren't you busy?

363
00:21:01,177 --> 00:21:02,762
I am.

364
00:21:02,845 --> 00:21:03,763
Then why?

365
00:21:04,555 --> 00:21:07,516
It seems like a good opportunity
to learn about the process.

366
00:21:08,267 --> 00:21:09,477
Do as you wish.

367
00:21:09,560 --> 00:21:10,644
Thank you, sir.

368
00:21:11,729 --> 00:21:14,774
I guess I'm finally taking on
a divorce case.

369
00:21:17,401 --> 00:21:18,569
I'm sorry for being late.

370
00:21:18,652 --> 00:21:21,322
Not at all. We were early.

371
00:21:22,782 --> 00:21:25,201
This is a paralegal from my team.

372
00:21:25,284 --> 00:21:27,787
I wanted to introduce you
to one of the unsung heroes

373
00:21:27,870 --> 00:21:30,873
behind the recent Seonul M&A
you spearheaded.

374
00:21:30,956 --> 00:21:33,667
I apologize for springing this on you.
Do you mind if he joins us?

375
00:21:33,751 --> 00:21:35,044
Not at all.

376
00:21:35,711 --> 00:21:37,797
Hello, ma'am.
My name is Choi Yun-geun.

377
00:21:38,464 --> 00:21:41,801
It's truly an honor to meet you like this.

378
00:21:41,884 --> 00:21:44,011
It's nice to meet you. Shall we sit?

379
00:21:44,094 --> 00:21:45,054
Sure.

380
00:21:46,972 --> 00:21:50,100
Mr. Choi here is actually a lawyer.

381
00:21:50,184 --> 00:21:52,728
Is that so?
Then why are you working as a paralegal?

382
00:21:54,897 --> 00:21:57,650
To tell you the truth,
I graduated from a regional law school,

383
00:21:57,733 --> 00:21:59,527
and my grades weren't great, either.

384
00:21:59,610 --> 00:22:02,446
And my bar exam score
was a bit low as well.

385
00:22:02,530 --> 00:22:06,200
I couldn't set foot
in a major firm like Yullim as a lawyer.

386
00:22:07,326 --> 00:22:08,410
I see.

387
00:22:08,911 --> 00:22:11,372
But when I put him to work,
I realized he's quite good.

388
00:22:11,455 --> 00:22:13,791
Unlike most young people nowadays,
he has good etiquette.

389
00:22:13,874 --> 00:22:16,043
And quite cost-effective as well.

390
00:22:16,126 --> 00:22:18,796
Paralegals cost a quarter
of what associates cost.

391
00:22:18,879 --> 00:22:19,755
I see.

392
00:22:19,839 --> 00:22:21,799
Someone as low on the ladder as me

393
00:22:21,882 --> 00:22:24,093
would never normally
get a chance to meet you.

394
00:22:24,176 --> 00:22:26,262
To share a meal with you like this

395
00:22:27,137 --> 00:22:28,514
is truly a great honor.

396
00:22:29,390 --> 00:22:31,016
Thank you for saying that.

397
00:22:34,979 --> 00:22:36,188
Thank you for the great meal.

398
00:22:36,272 --> 00:22:40,067
I'd be grateful for another chance
like this in the future.

399
00:22:40,860 --> 00:22:42,862
I enjoyed it as well.

400
00:22:43,654 --> 00:22:46,073
But please excuse me. I need to get going.

401
00:22:46,156 --> 00:22:47,283
Sure.

402
00:22:47,783 --> 00:22:49,410
Please let me pick up the check.

403
00:22:55,040 --> 00:22:58,586
I'm sorry, sir, but your card was denied.

404
00:22:59,503 --> 00:23:02,673
Pardon? That's not possible.

405
00:23:04,633 --> 00:23:07,136
Why don't you two go on ahead?

406
00:23:07,219 --> 00:23:08,888
Why? Is the card not going through?

407
00:23:09,513 --> 00:23:10,848
No, it's not that.

408
00:23:11,348 --> 00:23:13,684
Don't worry about it.
Just wait for me in the car.

409
00:23:13,767 --> 00:23:16,520
- Okay. Let's go.
- Okay.

410
00:23:19,398 --> 00:23:22,192
Sorry, just a second. That's weird.

411
00:23:22,276 --> 00:23:23,152
Mr. Lee!

412
00:23:26,906 --> 00:23:28,782
Gosh. Ms. Kwon.

413
00:23:31,869 --> 00:23:34,038
I'm terribly embarrassed.

414
00:23:34,121 --> 00:23:36,582
I'll be sure to pay you back later.

415
00:23:36,665 --> 00:23:38,709
It was my pleasure.

416
00:23:38,792 --> 00:23:40,336
Have you been well?

417
00:23:40,419 --> 00:23:43,297
I've been meaning to reach out
to see how you were doing.

418
00:23:43,380 --> 00:23:46,425
I guess you haven't heard.

419
00:23:46,508 --> 00:23:48,135
What do you mean?

420
00:23:50,054 --> 00:23:51,555
I lost my company.

421
00:23:52,348 --> 00:23:53,933
To Bluestone Fund.

422
00:23:54,016 --> 00:23:55,976
Pardon? How?

423
00:24:01,148 --> 00:24:02,691
Can you elaborate on what happened?

424
00:24:03,901 --> 00:24:05,903
As you well know,

425
00:24:05,986 --> 00:24:09,114
Hynic Core is like my life's work.

426
00:24:09,198 --> 00:24:10,980
The NPU design algorithm
and software platform…

427
00:24:11,055 --> 00:24:12,624
AI, MACHINE LEARNING OPTIMIZED PROCESSOR

428
00:24:12,790 --> 00:24:16,789
…were the result of years of dedication
by me and my research team.

429
00:24:16,872 --> 00:24:19,083
Yes, I'm well aware.

430
00:24:19,625 --> 00:24:23,295
Major corporations repeatedly tried
to buy your company for that technology.

431
00:24:23,379 --> 00:24:26,548
Yes, but one finally managed to succeed.

432
00:24:27,508 --> 00:24:29,760
Optalyn, a major U.S. corporation.

433
00:24:30,511 --> 00:24:33,847
Didn't you say you would never sell?

434
00:24:34,765 --> 00:24:38,060
I was not the one who sold it.
Bluestone Fund did.

435
00:24:39,269 --> 00:24:42,731
Bluestone initially invested
15 billion won in our company.

436
00:24:43,399 --> 00:24:45,192
They accused us
of embezzlement and whatnot

437
00:24:45,275 --> 00:24:46,986
before seizing
the entire company last year.

438
00:24:47,069 --> 00:24:50,990
In the end, they sold it
to Optalyn for 120 billion won.

439
00:24:51,657 --> 00:24:55,077
They bought it for 15 billion
and sold it for 120 billion.

440
00:24:56,996 --> 00:24:58,622
For a mere 120 billion won.

441
00:25:00,416 --> 00:25:03,085
Given the potential of that technology,

442
00:25:03,168 --> 00:25:04,837
that price was a joke.

443
00:25:05,462 --> 00:25:08,382
Bluestone has basically
sold out our country.

444
00:25:08,465 --> 00:25:11,385
They carelessly gave away
core technology developed in Korea

445
00:25:11,468 --> 00:25:14,013
to another nation,
just to line their own pockets.

446
00:25:15,264 --> 00:25:17,641
If we'd had the chance
to fully develop that technology,

447
00:25:17,725 --> 00:25:21,270
it could have fueled the next wave
of South Korea's economic growth.

448
00:25:23,772 --> 00:25:25,649
So that's what happened.

449
00:25:30,195 --> 00:25:33,657
Ms. Kwon met with Lee Seong-bin yesterday?

450
00:25:34,199 --> 00:25:35,409
All right.

451
00:25:42,875 --> 00:25:46,462
Hynic Core is Yullim's client,
not Lee Seong-bin.

452
00:25:46,545 --> 00:25:49,131
Mr. Lee didn't actually embezzle anything.

453
00:25:49,214 --> 00:25:50,841
- For the company's sake--
- Enough.

454
00:25:51,550 --> 00:25:52,885
Stop acting like an amateur.

455
00:25:52,968 --> 00:25:56,764
Aren't you aware that sort of consultation
directly violates the Attorney-at-Law Act?

456
00:25:58,265 --> 00:26:01,435
I'll call a partner meeting
to discuss this issue.

457
00:26:02,061 --> 00:26:03,604
You can explain yourself there.

458
00:26:03,687 --> 00:26:05,022
- Sir.
- You may leave.

459
00:26:26,668 --> 00:26:27,753
Hey.

460
00:26:27,836 --> 00:26:30,047
It appears we'll need
to fast-track the plan.

461
00:26:33,801 --> 00:26:35,469
Shouldn't we have a meeting?

462
00:26:35,552 --> 00:26:37,596
- About what?
- About Ms. Kwak Hye-jeong's divorce.

463
00:26:37,679 --> 00:26:39,723
I'll take care of that on my own.

464
00:26:40,474 --> 00:26:41,350
Why?

465
00:26:42,101 --> 00:26:44,269
What do you mean? It's my job.

466
00:26:44,353 --> 00:26:45,437
It's my case.

467
00:26:46,355 --> 00:26:48,857
No one said otherwise.
You hold onto that case.

468
00:26:48,941 --> 00:26:50,734
But I'm going to work on it by myself.

469
00:26:50,818 --> 00:26:51,944
I'll work on it too.

470
00:26:52,027 --> 00:26:54,238
Have you worked on a divorce case before?

471
00:26:54,321 --> 00:26:56,448
No. That's why I want to do it with you.

472
00:26:56,532 --> 00:26:57,950
That's why I want to work alone.

473
00:26:58,033 --> 00:26:59,034
Let's do it together.

474
00:27:00,202 --> 00:27:02,121
- What's up with you?
- That's what I want to ask.

475
00:27:02,204 --> 00:27:03,413
What do you mean?

476
00:27:03,497 --> 00:27:07,376
You don't talk to me, eat with me,
drink with me, or grab coffee with me.

477
00:27:08,001 --> 00:27:09,378
Now you won't even work with me.

478
00:27:10,796 --> 00:27:12,381
Did I do something to upset you?

479
00:27:12,464 --> 00:27:14,967
- No, you haven't.
- Then what's the matter?

480
00:27:17,219 --> 00:27:18,762
Let's not do this.

481
00:27:20,013 --> 00:27:21,223
Where are you taking me?

482
00:27:22,432 --> 00:27:23,684
What's wrong with you?

483
00:27:24,518 --> 00:27:25,394
I like you.

484
00:27:25,894 --> 00:27:26,770
What?

485
00:27:26,854 --> 00:27:27,855
No.

486
00:27:29,231 --> 00:27:30,190
I love you.

487
00:27:32,067 --> 00:27:33,360
You must have lost your mind.

488
00:27:33,443 --> 00:27:34,528
Yeah. I'm going insane.

489
00:27:35,279 --> 00:27:36,613
Move.

490
00:27:36,697 --> 00:27:38,824
- What do you want from me?
- I said I love you.

491
00:27:40,659 --> 00:27:41,660
Do you pity me?

492
00:27:41,743 --> 00:27:44,496
- As if you'd ever let me.
- This started after hearing about my past.

493
00:27:44,580 --> 00:27:46,248
Yeah, you're right.

494
00:27:46,790 --> 00:27:48,584
But I started liking you before that.

495
00:27:48,667 --> 00:27:49,751
I had feelings for you,

496
00:27:49,835 --> 00:27:52,963
but I held back because I didn't want
to ruin our relationship.

497
00:27:53,046 --> 00:27:55,132
But once I went from just liking you

498
00:27:55,215 --> 00:27:58,135
to liking you in spite of everything,
I knew for sure.

499
00:27:58,218 --> 00:28:00,929
I'm telling you
because it's eating me up inside.

500
00:28:01,638 --> 00:28:02,890
Because I'm about to go insane.

501
00:28:05,225 --> 00:28:06,727
That's just complete nonsense.

502
00:28:21,992 --> 00:28:24,870
SEOUL CENTRAL DISTRICT PROSECUTORS' OFFICE

503
00:28:24,953 --> 00:28:25,954
PROSECUTOR KWON WON-HYEOP

504
00:28:26,038 --> 00:28:27,873
So, what year are you?

505
00:28:27,956 --> 00:28:28,999
